abstract: It’s impossible to drive across the state and not be reminded of the first boundlessness of American potential.
snippet: It’s impossible to drive across the state and not be reminded of the first boundlessness of American potential.
lead_paragraph: NUCLA, Colo. — Richard Craig, gun lover, Trump hater, is the man behind the local ordinance here that made gun ownership obligatory for the head of every household. The unusual rule, approved overwhelmingly by the town board in 2013, has gained this small community in southwestern Colorado some notoriety. “I believe in our Constitution,” Craig told me. “Having our guns is just part of American freedom.” As for President Trump, “I think he’s an idiot. He should quit tweeting and keep his mouth shut.”

abstract: Mr. Gillum, the Democratic nominee for governor, supports higher corporate taxes and Medicare for all. He also has a lobbyist as a top adviser and, as mayor of Tallahassee, was on the payroll of a consultant.
snippet: Mr. Gillum, the Democratic nominee for governor, supports higher corporate taxes and Medicare for all. He also has a lobbyist as a top adviser and, as mayor of Tallahassee, was on the payroll of a consultant.
lead_paragraph: TALLAHASSEE, Fla. — City Hall never did seem big enough for Andrew Gillum.

abstract: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
snippet: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
lead_paragraph: World War II casts a long shadow across this week’s recommended titles. Nora Krug’s “Belonging” reckons with German guilt, both nationally and individually; Kate Atkinson’s “Transcription” sets a literary spy thriller amid Nazi sympathizers in London; and Joshua Cohen’s essay collection “Attention” ponders, among other things, the legacy of the Holocaust writer A. G. Adler. The Iraq war is here, too, in Elliot Ackerman’s novel “Waiting for Eden” and (by way of the protesters in its opening novella) in Toshiki Okada’s “The End of the Moment We Had.”
